Basic trees

tree <- read.tree("data/tree_newick.nwk")
tree
## 
## Phylogenetic tree with 13 tips and 12 internal nodes.
## 
## Tip labels:
##   A, B, C, D, E, F, ...
## 
## Rooted; includes branch lengths.
ggplot(tree) + geom_tree() + theme_tree()

ggtree(tree) + theme_tree2()

ggtree(tree, branch.length="none")

ggtree(tree, branch.length="none", color="blue", size=2, linetype=3)

Labeling clades

ggtree(tree) + 
  geom_tiplab() + 
  geom_cladelabel(node=17, label="Some random clade", 
                  color="red2", offset=.8, align=TRUE) + 
  geom_cladelabel(node=21, label="A different clade", 
                  color="blue", offset=.8, align=TRUE) +
  
  theme_tree2() + 
  xlim(0, 70) + 
  theme_tree()

ggtree(tree) + 
  geom_tiplab() + 
  geom_hilight(node=17, fill="gold") + 
  geom_hilight(node=21, fill="purple")

Connecting taxa

ggtree(tree) + 
  geom_tiplab() + 
  geom_taxalink("E", "H", color="blue3") +
  geom_taxalink("C", "G", color="orange2", curvature=-.9)

ggtree tutorial Exercise 3

## [1] 19
MRCA(tree, c("L", "J"))

ggtree(tree) + 
  geom_tiplab() + 
  geom_hilight(node=19, fill="blue") +

Bonus!

Many trees

set.seed(42)
trees <- lapply(rep(c(10, 25, 50, 100), 3), rtree)
class(trees) <- "multiPhylo"
ggtree(trees) + facet_wrap(~.id, scale="free", ncol=4) + ggtitle("Many trees. Such phylogenetics. Wow.")

Plot tree with other data

tree <- rtree(30)

p <- ggtree(tree)

d1 <- data.frame(id=tree$tip.label, val=rnorm(30, sd=3))

p2 <- facet_plot(p, panel="dot", data=d1, geom=geom_point, aes(x=val), color='red3')

d2 <- data.frame(id=tree$tip.label, value = abs(rnorm(30, mean=100, sd=50)))

p3 <- facet_plot(p2, panel='bar', data=d2, geom=geom_segment, 
           aes(x=0, xend=value, y=y, yend=y), size=3, color='blue4') 

p3 + theme_tree2()

Overlay organism silouhettes

newick <- "((Pongo_abelii,(Gorilla_gorilla_gorilla,(Pan_paniscus,Pan_troglodytes)Pan,Homo_sapiens)Homininae)Hominidae,Nomascus_leucogenys)Hominoidea;"

tree <- read.tree(text=newick)

d <- ggimage::phylopic_uid(tree$tip.label)
d$body_mass = c(52, 114, 47, 45, 58, 6)

p <- ggtree(tree) %<+% d + 
  geom_tiplab(aes(image=uid, colour=body_mass), geom="phylopic", offset=2.5) +
  geom_tiplab(aes(label=label), offset = .2) + xlim(NA, 7) +
  scale_color_viridis_c()
p
